<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSWIRE: CHRISTIE WINS 100 METERS IN 9.91 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SCOTT HOWARD-COOPER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Linford Christie completed a spectacular return to the Commonwealth Games in 
Victoria, Canada, on Tuesday, winning the 100 meters with the sixth-fastest 
time in history. 
</P>
<P>
 Christie, 34, won the gold medal in 9.91 seconds, his third games record in as 
many races over the past two days at Centennial Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
 "Age is in the mind," Christie said. "Everyday they keep telling me I'm old, 
but I'm still going out here and mixing it with the young ones and beating them 
all the time." 
</P>
<P>
 Christie, the world champion and 1992 Olympic gold medalist, won his 20th gold 
medal in an international competition and repeated as games champion. 
</P>
<P>
 Christie was the oldest entrant in the 100 meters. The second-oldest, Horace 
Dove-Edwards, 32, of Sierra Leone, was a surprising second in 10.02. The bronze 
medal went to Michael Green of Jamaica in 10.05. 
</P>
<P>
 Christie won his semifinal heat in 9.98, breaking the games record of 10.02 he 
set in New Zealand four years ago and tied in Monday's quarterfinals. 
Christie's winning time matched his wind-aided 9.91 of earlier this year. 
Basketball 
</P>
<P>
 The Lakers re-signed starting point guard Nick Van Exel and reserve forward 
Antonio Harvey, both restricted free agents. 
</P>
<P>
 Van Exel went from being a second-round draft choice with a one-year contract 
last season to becoming the Lakers' leader in minutes, assists and 
three-pointers. Harvey was undrafted out of tiny Pfeiffer College in 1993, but 
made the team and played in 27 games, with six starts. SCOTT HOWARD-COOPER 
</P>
</TEXT>
