<HEADLINE>
<P>
BELL TAKES INEVITABLE RELEASE HARD; PRO FOOTBALL: EX-RAIDER TAILBACK FIZZLES AT 
TIGHT END AND BLAMES SYSTEM. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE SPRINGER, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Nick Bell didn't want to get up Tuesday morning. 
</P>
<P>
 "I don't want to get out of bed," he told his wife, Pamela. "I don't want to 
get cut." 
</P>
<P>
 But he did get up. And he did get cut. 
</P>
<P>
 It was swift and expected, but being released by the Raiders was still painful 
for Bell, who was a highly regarded second-round draft choice only three years 
ago, an All-American running back from Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
 By 1992, Bell was sharing running back duties with Eric Dickerson and Marcus 
Allen. 
</P>
<P>
 By the summer of 1993, he was designated the starting tailback. 
</P>
<P>
 But it never happened. 
</P>
<P>
 Hit while he was going out of bounds after a five-yard gain in the second 
quarter of last year's exhibition finale against the Rams, Bell suffered a 
hamstring injury. By season's end, Bell suffered the indignity of being 
relegated to the bench as his team advanced to the second round of the 
playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
 By the summer of 1994, he was down to his last chance, signed to a $300,000 
contract and given an opportunity at tight end. 
</P>
<P>
 It wasn't really much of an opportunity. With the off-season departure of 
Ethan Horton, Andrew Glover had gotten the starting job. Veteran free agent 
Jamie Williams was signed as backup and Kevin Smith remained as a holdover from 
last season. 
</P>
<P>
 That left Bell fourth in a three-man rotation. Sixteen men have caught passes 
in the Raiders' four exhibition games. Bell was not among them. 
</P>
<P>
 "Opportunity is the key to everything," he said Tuesday morning as he loaded 
his bag into his vehicle after getting the official word from Steve Ortmayer, 
the Raiders' director of football operations. "The opportunity was not there." 
</P>
<P>
 Bell had gotten his final opportunity as a running back the day after 
Christmas last season. It was a miserable day for the Raiders, who suffered a 
28-0 defeat at the hands of the Packers in a game played in Green Bay 
zero-degree weather. 
</P>
<P>
 But none was more miserable than Bell. 
</P>
<P>
 Getting only his third start in his injury-marred season, Bell fumbled twice, 
dropped a pass and had another one nearly hit him in the back of the helmet 
when he failed to turn around. That was all before halftime. 
</P>
<P>
 For Bell, though, it was the end of the game. 
</P>
<P>
 He didn't get called on in the second half. Nor much after that. After a 
season-ending injury to Greg Robinson, the team's leading rusher, early in 
December, Bell finally had his long-awaited chance to regain the starting spot 
he had lost in the exhibition season. But he let it slip through his cold 
fingers that day in Green Bay. Bell got only two carries in the Raiders' two 
playoff games, gaining three yards. 
</P>
<P>
 "This offense was not designed for somebody who runs like I do," Bell said 
Tuesday. "That's why Leonard Russell isn't here. Or Rod Bernstine. That's why 
all the big backs aren't here. . . . This offense was designed for a scatback. 
I am not a scatback and never will be. 
</P>
<P>
 "I have good explosion. I run straight ahead. I run downhill, but I'm not the 
type of guy who is going to run around somebody. Every time I try to do that, I 
hurt myself. I'm not a Bo Jackson. This offense is all about Bo and Marcus 
(Allen) and those kinds of guys. It's unfair to me. I don't have 4.2 or 4.3 
speed. I don't have the type of explosion (Jackson) had. I wasn't 230 pounds. I 
was 20 pounds heavier than him. What do you expect? Be realistic in your goals. 
Don't try to make somebody into something they're not. 
</P>
<P>
 "I hope you don't paint a picture of me as being bitter because I'm not. I'm 
just looking at it realistically." 
</P>
<P>
 Bell's best season was 1992, when he gained 366 yards, averaged 4.5 a carry 
and scored three touchdowns. He also rushed for 107 yards in a 1991 playoff 
game. 
</P>
<P>
 What now? Bell wants to return to school and eventually go into business for 
himself, but he's still interested in football. 
</P>
<P>
 "I've never been one to give up and I still haven't given up," he said. "The 
fact is, I always tried the best I could, even when I had a torn hamstring. I 
was still out there six weeks later, hobbling on it, practicing, playing in 
games. For who? Myself? I don't think so, because it hurt me. Look at where I 
am now." 
</P>
</TEXT>
