<HEADLINE>
<P>
QUESTIONS SURROUND KARIYA TALKS; HOCKEY: DUCKS' DRAFTEE WAITS FOR ANOTHER 
CONTRACT OFFER WHILE EXPLORING POSSIBILITY OF NOT SIGNING IN ORDER TO BE A FREE 
AGENT NEXT SEASON. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ROBYN NORWOOD, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Paul Kariya is awaiting a new contract offer from the Mighty Ducks this week, 
and agent Don Baizley said Kariya then will have to wrestle with a decision -- 
whether to sign or pursue an NHL ruling Baizley believes would make his client 
a free agent for the 1995-96 season if he sits out this season. 
</P>
<P>
 The catch could end up being this: The league is declining to give a rules 
interpretation on a hypothetical situation, meaning Kariya might have to make a 
decision without knowing its repercussions. 
</P>
<P>
 That, as negotiations go, would be a point for the Ducks. 
</P>
<P>
 Talks have remained amicable despite a pace so creeping that Duck General 
Manager Jack Ferreira says the headline when Kariya signs -- if he signs -- 
should be, "Finally." 
</P>
<P>
 The key sticking point this summer has been Baizley's request for a 
clarification on Kariya's status should he not sign this year. Unsigned draft 
picks typically return to the draft after two years, or one year after leaving 
college. But Baizley says that because Kariya would be classified as a 
21-year-old under NHL rules and therefore too old to qualify for next June's 
entry draft, he should become an unrestricted free agent. 
</P>
<P>
 His appeals to Commissioner Gary Bettman have been fruitless, however, and 
league spokesman Arthur Pincus said Tuesday Bettman will not rule until there 
is an actual dispute. The implication is that Bettman won't make an 
interpretation that could be used in negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
 Nevertheless, Baizley said he is confident Kariya would become a free agent. 
(Ferreira says the Ducks don't care if he could become a free agent, they only 
want to sign him.) 
</P>
<P>
 With training camp scheduled to open Sept. 4 in Anaheim and the season 
scheduled to begin Oct. 1, "we all realize time is closing in," Baizley said. 
</P>
<P>
 The Ducks, who say there is nothing new to report in the negotiations, will 
offer Kariya a contract richer than the three-year $4.2 million deal they gave 
this year's second overall pick, Oleg Tverdovsky. Tverdovsky's deal pays an 
average $1.8 million a year before the third year, which calls for an option 
year salary of $600,000 that probably will be renegotiated. 
</P>
<P>
 Kariya is believed to be seeking more than $2 million a year. 
</P>
<P>
 Kariya is declining interviews, but Baizley said "he is being typically 
thoughtful Paul, trying to examine his options." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
