<HEADLINE>
<P>
CROWDED TABLE AS NEGOTIATIONS RESUME TODAY; BASEBALL: SEVERAL DOZEN PLAYERS, 
REPRESENTATIVES OF OWNERS ARE EXPECTED TO ATTEND, BUT THERE IS LITTLE HOPE. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ROSS NEWHAN, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Prodded by federal mediators, baseball's collective bargaining will resume 
today. Will it go beyond today? Is there anything new to discuss? 
</P>
<P>
 Only if owners withdraw the salary cap that has polarized the sides and shut 
down negotiations since the strike by major league players began on Aug. 12. 
</P>
<P>
 On Day 12 of the strike Tuesday, there was some seeming flexibility offered by 
Boston Red Sox CEO John Harrington regarding the owners' willingness to look at 
alternatives, but no firm indication that the cap is coming off -- either today 
or in the near future. 
</P>
<P>
 Harrington, the moderate CEO of the big-market Red Sox and spokesman for the 
owners' pool, was asked if the owners are prepared to let go of the cap. 
</P>
<P>
 "Not at this time," he said. "We still feel it's in the best interest of the 
game." 
</P>
<P>
 He said the owners remain united behind the need for change in the 
compensation system and keep hoping and waiting for the union to respond to 
their proposal. 
</P>
<P>
 He added, however, that if the union has better ideas there are "no limits" to 
the owners' willingness to discuss alternatives. 
</P>
<P>
 "There's absolutely no way we'll go for a salary cap, but get rid of it and 
we'll talk about anything," said Dodger player representative Brett Butler, one 
of 18 players who met with four mediators after the mediators had met with the 
pool of 12 owners and club executives. 
</P>
<P>
 In response to a request by owners negotiator Richard Ravitch, mediators 
agreed to let all 12 attend today's negotiations, a decision that drew no 
objection from the players union, which might have twice as many players and 
has been eager to confront the owners. 
</P>
<P>
 "It should be a rich mix," said John Calhoun Wells, national director of the 
Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service in reference to the crowded table. 
</P>
<P>
 Both Ravitch and Donald Fehr, the union's executive director, expressed hope 
that a dialogue can accelerate a settlement, but there were no promises. 
</P>
<P>
 "We've heard rumors that the owners might have a second proposal," Kansas City 
Royal pitcher David Cone said. "That's the kind of thing we're looking forward 
to finding out." 
</P>
<P>
 A second proposal? 
</P>
<P>
 "Clearly not," acting commissioner Bud Selig said from Milwaukee. "The only 
thing you may have been hearing is that we have cost problems that have to be 
dealt with, and revenue sharing (without the cap) isn't enough. If the union 
has any devices for dealing with the problems, we'll be happy to discuss them. 
That's all anyone is saying." 
</P>
<P>
 Said Ravitch, when asked if the cap was still on the table: "I'm not going to 
comment on that, but I don't want to suggest by my silence that the proposal 
has changed. It's fair to say the owners have not changed their view on the 
need for cost certainty." 
</P>
<P>
 The union recently presented the owners a series of revenue-sharing 
alternatives without a cap and saw them rejected. 
</P>
<P>
 "If the alternative is a functional equivalent of a cap, we don't draw the 
distinction," said Fehr, who added that the owners are still tied to the 
historical baggage of previous negotiations -- this is the eighth stoppage 
since 1972 -- and still attempting to put artificial limitations on a free 
market. 
</P>
<P>
 If there is a compromise in the stalemate, most believe it rests in the 
players' willingness to eliminate or modify salary arbitration in exchange for 
earlier free agency and removal of the cap. 
</P>
<P>
 Fehr, however, said that's not what the owners mean when they bring up 
alternatives. He says they are merely expressing a willingness to change the 
percentages of their proposal -- they have offered the union 50% of all revenue 
-- if the union will tell them what it wants. 
</P>
<P>
 Fehr has refused to provide an answer because it would be accepting the cap. 
He says a free market should determine what the players earn. 
</P>
<P>
 In the meantime, the union has sent a recently completed economic study of the 
industry to each of the clubs. The report, commissioned by the union, was done 
by Stanford economist Roger Noll and reaches the same conclusions as a 1985 
study by Noll: The industry is not in the trouble the owners say it is. 
</P>
<P>
 Thus, the battle lines remain drawn as the season evaporates and Fehr and 
Ravitch continue to throw verbal darts at one another. 
</P>
<P>
 "I note Don said yesterday that he's never seen me in a team picture," Ravitch 
said. "Well, I've never seen him in uniform on a (bubble gum) card either. 
That's not our job. We're not players and we're not owners. Don is a very 
capable negotiator and we're here to facilitate a settlement." 
</P>
<P>
 They will be accompanied by the players and owners today, but that doesn't 
mean that a settlement is any closer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA082494-0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 072603 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
August 24, 1994, Wednesday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part C; Page 5; Column 1; Sports Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1300 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
RIDE THE WILD TURF; JOHN TOMAC, TINKER JUAREZ WILL BATTLE FOR NATIONAL MOUNTAIN 
BIKE TITLE IN BIG BEAR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RICH ROBERTS, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 At first they will suffer from oxygen debt, with interest, especially at such 
a high elevation as Big Bear Lake's 6,700 feet, where the NORBA National 
Mountain Bike Championships are scheduled this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
 "That's sort of a tingly, lightheaded feeling," John Tomac explains. "You have 
to recover from that. And then later in the race when you start running out of 
glycogen, you lose all your energy." 
</P>
<P>
 Glycogen is the starchy stuff stored in the liver and muscles that the body 
turns into sugar when the energy alarm goes off. 
</P>
<P>
 When the glycogen gauge reads empty, David (Tinker) Juarez says, "You feel it 
mainly in your legs."  
</P>
<P>
 Then, perhaps, come heat exhaustion -- and that's only the physical part. 
</P>
<P>
 "I could just choke from the pressure," Juarez says. 
</P>
<P>
 Tomac sometimes does that to his rivals. At 26, he could become the first to 
accomplish what few mountain bike competitors have even attempted: winning both 
the national cross-country and downhill championships in the same year. The 
downhill is virtually assured, unless he falls on his head or the bike breaks, 
none of which he discounts, based on experience. 
</P>
<P>
 But he must beat Juarez to win the cross-country title, and endurance plays an 
important role in that 32-mile race. 
</P>
<P>
 Tomac leads Juarez by two points, 227-225. The winner gets 60, the runner-up 
55. Nobody else is a factor as they come into the national finals, the last of 
six events on the National Off-Road Bicycle Assn. (NORBA) tour that has wound 
around the country from Georgia to Michigan to Vermont to Mammoth Lakes to 
Spokane to Big Bear Lake. 
</P>
<P>
 This week's competition is being staged by Team Big Bear at the Snow Summit 
skiing complex, where more than 2,500 men and women will ride cross-country, 
downhill and double slalom in various divisions based on age, gender and skill. 
The top six finishers in each division advance to next month's world 
championships at Vail, Colo. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Mountain biking has become popular in the last decade and its natural 
evolution into racing has been even more recent, drawing competitors who grew 
up in BMX -- the little bikes -- racing over artificial bumps and jumps. In 
1996 it will enter the lofty realm of the Olympics when cross-country becomes a 
formal event of the Atlanta Games. 
</P>
<P>
 Some top riders, such as Tomac and Juarez, already have found they can make a 
decent living at it. The prize money isn't quite enough -- the winners earn 
only $2,200 in cross-country and $1,500 in downhill, and the total purse is 
$200,000. But most riders receive team salaries and supplement those with 
endorsements. Tomac rides for Tioga/Raleigh, Juarez for Volvo/Cannondale. The 
top five might earn $100,000-$150,000 a year, Tomac maybe $250,000 or better. 
</P>
<P>
 Tomac hopes to add to his earnings in the cross-country race, scheduled for 1 
p.m. Saturday. If successful, he will try to complete his double by clinching 
the downhill title Sunday morning. It's an iron-man order. Only one other 
rider, Jed Fox, is even listed in the top 30 in both disciplines, and he's 22nd 
and 30th. 
</P>
<P>
 "It is a busy schedule, but I enjoy doing both events, and I'm good at both, 
so there's no reason not to," Tomac says. "Usually, the cross-country race 
takes quite a bit out of my legs, so I'm at a bit of a disadvantage for the 
downhill. But if I do it right I can get away with being a little bit tired." 
</P>
<P>
 Rivals are in awe of Tomac. He is the face of his sport in this country, 
fulfilling PR obligations but preferring time with his wife, Kathy, two sons, 
two Bernese mountain dogs and five turkeys at their home outside Durango, 
Colo., an out-of-the-way town that has become a haven for mountain bikers. 
</P>
<P>
 When Tomac really wants to hide, he retreats to his 800-acre ranch near 
Cortez, Colo., where Kathy says they plan to retire, as if 26-year-olds think 
about retiring. 
</P>
<P>
 Most of the riders carry less body fat than a ghost, but even at a lean 
5-feet-10 and 160 pounds, Tomac is slightly oversize for a cross-country racer. 
Going uphill he spots rivals as much as 20 pounds. Downhill he makes it up, and 
Juarez's strategy revolves around those factors. 
</P>
<P>
 "I just need to beat John," Juarez says. "I'm thinking that he's going to want 
to be the guy that leads the race. It's going to be a long race, close to three 
hours, so my main goal is to stay on him and find out where his strong and weak 
points are. He could feel good or he might be a little slow in certain spots." 
</P>
<P>
 Juarez learned about pacing by running in four L.A. Marathons, 1988-91. His 
best time was 2 hours 39 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm not going to go out and try to lead the race," he says. "A lot of riders 
do that and fade far back. (Tomac has) done that quite often, and usually the 
riders behind end up catching him." 
</P>
<P>
 But Tomac says he has learned, too. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm a lot more experienced now," he says. "I know what it takes to win and 
how to get to the finish line the fastest." 
</P>
<P>
 Juarez figures he's the cat and Tomac's the mouse. 
</P>
<P>
 "I don't want him to get out of sight, and if he does jump out in front I'm 
going to stay on his wheel until I know where I'm going to set him up at the 
end." 
</P>
<P>
 Juarez thinks he may be able to reduce Tomac's edge by getting in front uphill 
and blocking him on the downhill sections where the course is tight. Juarez is 
cautious going downhill. 
</P>
<P>
 "I might be good, but I'm far from a gonzo rider," he has said. "I fear for 
getting hurt. I don't like to go too extreme down the hills because I don't 
want to crash or get a mechanical problem. (Tomac) kind of lets it all out." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Juarez, 33, is from Norwalk but lives at Sugar Loaf, near Big Bear Lake, with 
his fiancee, Sara Ellis, who is also a bike racer. Everybody calls him Tinker, 
not David. His mother, Rose, is his agent and publicist but may lose her job 
after he reads how he got his nickname. 
</P>
<P>
 "Nobody knows this story," she says. "When he was a couple of months old, 
every time I changed his diaper he would 'tinker' all over. So I used to say, 
'You little tinker you,' and everybody around me would say, 'You little 
tinker.' He's told different stories, but that's the real one." 
</P>
<P>
 Tinker may hear about that from his rivals -- especially Tomac. 
</P>
<P>
 Tomac has finished ahead of Juarez in three of the five NORBA events this 
year. He won all three, with Juarez second -- once by a bike length. When 
Juarez won at Vermont, Tomac was fourth, and when Juarez finished fifth at 
Mammoth Lakes, Tomac dropped out, still suffering after-effects of the flu. 
That became each rider's "throw-out" race for the series. 
</P>
<P>
 "My goal is only to beat Tinker and win the title," Tomac says. "I don't care 
if we're racing for 15th place or first. He's been consistent this year. It'll 
be interesting to see how prepared he is for this last race. I mean, I know how 
to beat the guy. It's just a matter of doing it one more time." 
</P>
<P>
 Tomac has had enough bad luck, such as flat tires and breakdowns, to keep him 
from winning more than one national title. Juarez hasn't won any but has been 
close enough twice to figure he deserves one. 
</P>
<P>
 "I've been in this position twice in my career and been choking at the end," 
he says. "I know about blowing it at the last race." 
</P>
<P>
 Juarez won a World Cup event at Mt. Ste. Anne, Canada, in '93 but missed the 
national title by placing third to Tomac at Michigan. However, it could hardly 
be called a "choke" in '91 when he was leading in points going into the Big 
Bear Lake race and needed only to finish in the top 10 to claim the title. 
Instead, he suffered two flat tires. 
</P>
<P>
 "I feel pretty psyched that I'm going to do well," Juarez says. "My strategy 
is just to have a strong race and not ride over my head. I'm going to try to 
pretend that it's just another race and go in more relaxed. He's really going 
to make the pressure hard on me. If I want it bad enough, I'll have to prove 
him wrong."  
</P>
</TEXT>
