<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY PERSPECTIVE; SAFETY FIRST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Last month, a smoldering cigarette tossed from a passing car touched off a 
one-acre fire near the ignition point of last October's devastating Laguna 
Beach fire. Last weekend, a rifle bullet fired at a metal target ignited a 
brush fire that blackened 180 acres in the Cleveland National Forest.And the 
worst of the Southern California fire season is not yet upon us. 
</P>
<P>
 One top official of the Los Angeles County Fire Department warned last week 
that dry weather and brush have created a potential for disastrous fires. The 
traditional fire season will not begin until next month but already there have 
been flare-ups that are worrisome, particularly at a time when memories of last 
year's fires in Altadena, Malibu and Laguna Beach are so fresh. 
</P>
<P>
 Some individuals' lack of safety concern has been astounding. One Orange 
County fire official said he was speechless at learning that someone had 
discarded a burning cigarette in an area where 400 homes were destroyed by fire 
in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
 The Cleveland National Forest blaze also illustrated the need for caution. A 
firearms instructor told investigators that one shot from a rifle at a metal 
target set off sparks that ignited the fire, which spread from private property 
to the federal forest. The no doubt unintentional disregard of the dangerously 
dry conditions resulted in the need to call in hundreds of firefighters and 
three water-dropping helicopters. 
</P>
<P>
 After a year of little rain and with the Santa Ana winds on the horizon, it is 
especially important now to clear brush and use common sense. 
</P>
</TEXT>
