<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: SEAL BEACH; FRESHLY PAINTED JAIL IS OPEN FOR BUSINESS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RUSS LOAR 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Orange County's first privately run jail is now open for business. And with a 
fresh coat of paint, laundry-fresh linens and remote-control color televisions 
in the larger cells, the Seal Beach City Jail is almost like home. 
</P>
<P>
 Except for those big iron doors. 
</P>
<P>
 Bud Grossman, former Western Region director of the federal Bureau of Prisons, 
spent $50,000 to renovate the never-used City Jail, which he expects to 
generate a profit for himself and for the city. The new jail opened about three 
weeks ago behind the Seal Beach Boulevard police station. 
</P>
<P>
 Grossman figures that after the first year of operation the jail will earn the 
city about $100,000 a year in fees from other cities and law enforcement 
agencies that use the jail. Some prisoners will have the option of paying to 
stay at the City Jail to avoid incarceration at the County Jail in Santa Ana. 
</P>
<P>
 "People would rather be in this small jail than the county jail," said 
Grossman, a 62-year-old Brea resident who was appointed by a federal court to 
oversee conditions in the Orange County Jail from 1985 to 1988. "They feel 
safer here." 
</P>
<P>
 City and police officials say the privately run jail is one of only a few such 
facilities in the state and the only one in Orange County. Irvine has a 
privately run holding facility. 
</P>
<P>
 The jail, which can house 30 inmates in six cells, has a large, rubber-floored 
detoxification room. The maximum stay is one year. Only low- to moderate-risk 
prisoners will be held at the City Jail, where there are currently three men 
convicted of drunk driving and an embezzler. All four prisoners leave the jail 
during the day on work furloughs and return each night. They were ordered by 
the court to pay the city for the cost of their imprisonment. 
</P>
<P>
 Although City Council members were initially concerned about the safety of a 
privately run jail, they unanimously approved the venture last April, saying it 
would help increase badly needed revenues without raising taxes. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's cheaper than if we ran it ourselves," said Mayor George Brown, adding 
that the jail was never used after its construction in 1978 because of concerns 
over operating costs. 
</P>
<P>
 The new jail also saves the city the $158-per-prisoner booking fee charged by 
the County Jail. But police say those charged with more serious crimes such as 
rape, armed robbery and murder will continue to be sent to County Jail. 
</P>
<P>
 Jail employees are hired and trained by Grossman's company, Corrections 
Services Inc. But Seal Beach police Capt. Gary Maiten oversees jail operations, 
and the city has the right to close the jail within 180 days if the experiment 
proves unsuccessful. The city and Grossman's company split operating costs. 
</P>
<P>
 Grossman said San Diego has the only other privately run city jail in the 
state. The Seal Beach jail is his first entrepreneurial venture, but Grossman 
sees a growth market in crime, thanks to prison overcrowding and the high cost 
of building new facilities. His next project is the creation of a 320-bed 
prison for youthful offenders in Century, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
 "There are about 90 privately operated jails and prisons throughout the 
country," Grossman said. "That's only 2% of the market. There's plenty of room 
to grow."RUSS LOAR 
</P>
</TEXT>
