<HEADLINE>
<P>
U.S. MAY LIFT MOST SANCTIONS AGAINST CHINA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JIM MANN, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Clinton Administration is weighing a possible end to most remaining 
sanctions that the United States imposed on China for crushing the 1989 
democracy protests in Tian An Men Square, despite President Clinton's 
assurances three months ago that he was extending the restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
 Commerce Secretary Ronald H. Brown confirmed Tuesday that the Administration 
is thinking about lifting the prohibitions on U.S. trade assistance to China 
and on the Overseas Private Investment Corp. program, which provides insurance 
and financing for American companies. These are virtually the last two 
sanctions left in effect from the time of the Beijing massacre. 
</P>
<P>
 At a breakfast, Brown characterized Clinton's policy toward China as "in 
transition." Brown is preparing to play a central role in the policy changes 
when he flies to Beijing on Saturday as head of an official, White 
House-sponsored delegation of American business leaders seeking commercial 
contracts in China. 
</P>
<P>
 His remarks were the latest indications that, in the wake of Clinton's 
decision in May to unconditionally extend China's trade benefits in this 
country, the Administration is moving rapidly to restore and upgrade relations 
with Beijing's Communist leadership. 
</P>
<P>
 Last week, Defense Secretary William J. Perry welcomed to the Pentagon Xu 
Huizi, who as deputy chief of staff is one of the top leaders of the People's 
Liberation Army. Perry greeted him with an honor cordon, a lunch and extensive 
talks. They were the highest-level U.S. contacts with the Chinese military 
since it shot its way into downtown Beijing in 1989, killing about 1,000 people 
by Western estimates. 
</P>
<P>
 The Administration also plans to invite Chinese Foreign Minister Qian Qichen 
to Washington for an official visit in September, and Perry is expected to 
visit Beijing in October. 
</P>
<P>
 The Administration's China policy is starting to attract the same 
denunciations from Republicans that former President George Bush got from 
Democrats. Last week, Sen. Hank Brown (R-Colo.) contended that the warm welcome 
given to the Chinese general was "a mark of shame upon everyone associated with 
this kind of ceremony." 
</P>
<P>
 In his speech at the Democratic National Convention accepting the presidential 
nomination, Clinton attacked the Bush Administration for "coddling dictators" 
in Beijing. Between 1989 and 1992, other Democratic leaders criticized Bush and 
his top aides for sending then-National Security Adviser Brent Scowcroft on a 
conciliatory visit to Beijing six months after the crackdown. 
</P>
<P>
 But when asked Tuesday how Clinton's policy toward China differs from Bush's, 
Brown did not mention human rights. Instead, he responded that the 
Administration has opened the way for a "new commercial relationship" with 
Beijing. 
</P>
<P>
 He said Clinton is moving toward "a greater engagement that we believe can 
lead to an enhanced relationship which is good for both China and the United 
States." 
</P>
<P>
 On May 26, when Clinton granted China an unconditional extension of its trade 
privileges in this country, he said he would leave intact sanctions imposed on 
China in 1989. "In view of the continuing human rights abuses, I am extending 
the sanctions imposed by the United States as a result of the events in Tian An 
Men Square," he said in a televised news conference. 
</P>
<P>
 His pledge to extend the sanctions apparently was aimed at easing the impact 
of his most-favored-nation decision and deflecting possible congressional 
criticism. Earlier this month, the House voted, 270 to 158, to uphold his 
policy on most-favored-nation status for China. 
</P>
<P>
 Clinton's claim was somewhat misleading, because by May a number of the 
sanctions imposed in 1989 had already been lifted. 
</P>
<P>
 The Bush Administration had opened the way for resumed high-level official 
visits between Washington and Beijing and had given a green light for renewed 
World Bank lending to China. The Clinton Administration had ended sanctions on 
U.S.-China military contacts and on official, regular exchanges by 
Cabinet-level commissions. 
</P>
<P>
 There are three Tian An Men Square sanctions still in effect: the ban on OPIC 
insurance guarantees for American companies, the prohibition on trade 
development assistance and the sanction prohibiting official U.S. military 
sales to China. 
</P>
<P>
 Brown indicated Tuesday that the Administration is talking about lifting the 
first two sanctions, both of which involve government support for American 
business in China. "No decision has been made," he said. But he said ending the 
two restrictions is "being considered -- action to be taken on them in the 
future." 
</P>
<P>
 If the Administration terminates these sanctions, the only significant 
restriction left would be the prohibition against American military sales to 
China. No one believes this ban will be lifted anytime soon, in part because 
China has little interest in having it lifted. 
</P>
<P>
 Chinese officials do not want to buy more U.S. military equipment, because 
they were badly burned when the post-1989 sanctions caused several military 
programs to be held up for three years. 
</P>
<P>
 Brown said Tuesday that while he is in Beijing he will meet with Premier Li 
Peng, who was closely involved in the 1989 crackdown on democracy forces and 
has served as the action's principal defender since that time. He said he may 
also meet with Chinese President Jiang Zemin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
