<HEADLINE>
<P>
SENATE OKS BILL ON RIGHTS FOR UNWED COUPLES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CARL INGRAM, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Senate narrowly passed legislation Tuesday night allowing gay and other 
unwed couples to register as domestic partners to obtain limited benefits 
reserved for married people. 
</P>
<P>
 The measure by Assemblyman Richard Katz (D-Sylmar) was approved by a 21-17 
vote, the exact majority required in the 40-member Senate, and returned to the 
Assembly for approval of Senate amendments. Gov. Pete Wilson has not taken a 
position on the bill, a spokesman for the governor said. 
</P>
<P>
 For hours, the bill lingered one vote short of passage. It won approval when 
Democratic Sen. Leroy Greene (D-Carmichael) left the sickbed where he was 
recovering from surgery and cast the crucial 21st vote. 
</P>
<P>
 The bill (AB 2810) would enable unmarried couples, regardless of sex, to 
officially register their "domestic partnership" with the secretary of state. 
It specifically prohibits any other benefits. 
</P>
<P>
 Registered domestic partners would be allowed to visit their companions at 
hospitals on the same basis as close family members and would be permitted to 
act as conservators for each other. 
</P>
<P>
 "These are very minimal rights. They are rights that every couple, every 
individual, ought to have an opportunity to participate in," said Sen. Gary K. 
Hart (D-Santa Barbara). 
</P>
<P>
 In recent years, similar legislative efforts have failed, chiefly because of 
opposition from conservative Christians, who say such bills erode legal rights 
traditionally reserved for married couples. 
</P>
<P>
 But this session, Katz and his supporters -- including religious, labor, 
health, civil rights and senior citizens organizations -- changed tactics. They 
marketed the bill as offering a humanitarian hand to unmarried senior citizens. 
</P>
<P>
 Hart said some unmarried elderly people live together for "companionship, 
security and independence." He said they often choose not to marry because that 
would reduce their Social Security benefits. 
</P>
<P>
 But opponents of the bill also shifted their lobbying tactics to meet the 
challenge. The Traditional Values Coalition added to its list of moral 
arguments an assertion that the bill would be bad for business in California. 
</P>
<P>
 The coalition said the bill may undercut court decisions and result in 
extension of employment-related benefits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
