<HEADLINE>
<P>
ONLY IN L.A. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Steve Harvey 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 His ears were burning: Pressure is mounting on the European Union Council of 
Ministers, which has slapped a quota on the importation of "non-human" dolls by 
Great Britain from China. That includes Spock dolls from the "Star Trek" 
series. 
</P>
<P>
 Batman and Robin eluded the quota, as did Captain Kirk. 
</P>
<P>
 Actor Leonard Nimoy, who played the big-eared Vulcan, dispatched a letter of 
protest to the Wall Street Journal from this solar system (if you consider 
Beverly Hills down to earth). In the letter, published Tuesday, Nimoy said that 
depriving "the English people of the company of such a favorite seems to me a 
sadly inhuman act." 
</P>
<P>
 The Star Trek Fan Club, possibly laying the groundwork for a lawsuit, has 
already pointed out that Spock had a human mother. 
</P>
<P>
 Guess we'll have to wait for the results of the DNA test. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Your tax dollars at work: R. Douglas Collins sent us a travel schedule drawn 
up by the city administrative officer for L.A. employees, which lists $442 as 
the cost of a flight from L.A. to . . . Oxnard/Ventura. 
</P>
<P>
 Yes, that Oxnard/Ventura. 
</P>
<P>
 With the cost increasing to $489 by 1995. 
</P>
<P>
 Contacted by your crusading Only in L.A. reporter, the city controller's 
office -- the expense account police -- sounded a warning to city employees to 
ignore that bargain. 
</P>
<P>
 "Why would anyone fly to Oxnard?" said Deputy Controller Irene Lim after she 
had stopped laughing. "It must be a typographical error. Oxnard's only 50 miles 
away. It's only an hour for driving. How much earlier would you get there by 
plane, especially if you had to fly out of Burbank or LAX?" 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Who says L.A. has no roots?Certainly not the Roto-Rooter Corp., which lists 
three L.A. tree branches among the 10 largest ever unearthed by the company's 
workers.  
</P>
<P>
 The local king was a 103-foot, 7-inch root that workers Les Estes and 
Christopher Starks pulled out of a pipe last year Downtown near the World Trade 
Center. 
</P>
<P>
 That gem fell just 11 inches short of the all-time record root, found in 
Provo, Utah, in 1954. We're sure that L.A. would have had even more impressive 
stats if it hadn't been for the many drought years. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 The real estate market's really getting vicious: Paul Spix of Diamond Bar 
photographed a sign put up by a property owner who seems to be warning 
potential buyers that he plays hardball. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Billboard jungle: You may have noticed that the California Egg Council is 
phasing out that non sequitur of a billboard that said: "22% Less Cholesterol 4 
Times a Week," which implied that the chickens were laying less healthy eggs 
Thursday through Saturday. The replacement proclaims: "4 Times a Week Is 
Healthy." 
</P>
<P>
 Meanwhile, the bad timing award goes to Fox TV, which put up anonymous mystery 
billboards all over town that said: "The Rams Are Moving." The network has 
since added: "To Fox 11," a reference to the fact that Fox outbid CBS for the 
NFC football games. 
</P>
<P>
 But the ad campaign comes at a time when the Rams are contacting nearly every 
city in the nation, asking if they can come live there. Perhaps, because of the 
high airline rates, they haven't asked Oxnard. miscelLAny: 
</P>
<P>
 This make you feel old? When Disneyland opened in 1954, the futuristic 
Tomorrowland attraction was supposed to reflect the world of "the late 1980s." 
</P>
